text:
ok i found the memory thing. i'm writing this up while it's hot because if i don't, in three months i'll wonder how i fixed it and have to re-derive. so. context first: routeopt rust migration, axum service, tokio runtime, sqlx for postgres + my custom postgis encoder. each incoming request spawns a tokio task that does the optimization work, returns json. simple. last week i noticed memory growth under sustained load with realistic stop counts (~80+ stops per request).

hypothesis was: large vec moved into spawned closure, captured allocation kept alive longer than expected. close, but wrong. the actual cause was more interesting and dumber. here's the path:

the optimizer takes a `vec<stop>` and runs a bunch of distance computations on it. internally we cache the haversine distances in a `vec<vec<f32>>` matrix, n×n. for n=80 stops that's 6400 f32s, 25.6kb. fine. but i was building this matrix inside an `arc<routeoptimizer>` that lives for the lifetime of the request — and the arc was being cloned into a sub-spawn for the parallel-search portion of the algorithm. the sub-spawn is supposed to drop the arc when done. it does. but the parent task holds a reference too, and the parent task is held alive by... a tokio mpsc receiver waiting on its result. and that receiver is held alive by... the axum response future. you see where this is going.

the responsefuture wasn't dropping the receiver promptly because i had a `tokio::select!` upstream that was branching on either-result-or-timeout, and the timeout branch wasn't explicitly canceling the result side. so under sustained load, with 1% of requests hitting the timeout branch, those requests' optimizer arcs were not getting dropped, the matrices were sticking around, and we were leaking ~25kb every couple thousand requests. the math worked: 40mb of growth over 30 minutes ≈ 1600 hung optimizers, which matched my error rate.

the debugging path was painful and i want to record it because the next time i see slow memory growth in tokio i'm going to want to remember the playbook:

step 1 — i ran `valgrind --tool=massif` on a release build (yes, massif works on rust if you let it run for a while). showed me the heap-residency curve in 5-minute snapshots. confirmed growth was monotonic, didn't plateau, didn't release on idle. so it wasn't fragmentation, it was actual retained allocations. massif on a tokio service is unfun because the tokio runtime has its own internal allocations and they show up as background noise in every snapshot, but if you sort by 'change since last snapshot' you can see what's actually growing. the growth was concentrated in two stack frames: the haversine matrix allocation and a clone happening inside the spawn closure. that narrowed the search a lot.

step 2 — i used `tokio-console` to inspect task states. saw a bunch of tasks in 'idle (waiting)' state that should not exist. counted them. the count tracked memory growth almost exactly. that was the first big tell — it wasn't a leaky allocation pattern, it was a leaky task pattern. tokio-console is criminally underused, btw. it's the rust equivalent of `top -o tasks` for an async runtime. five minutes of staring at it told me more than an hour of valgrind.

step 3 — i added a `pin_project::pin_project` instrumentation around the response future to log when it dropped. immediately saw the asymmetry: under nominal load, every spawned task had a corresponding drop log. under burst load, ~1% of tasks had no drop log. those were the orphaned tasks. drop logs in async rust are weirdly hard to add cleanly because of the move semantics around pinned futures, but pin_project makes it bearable. there's a pattern in the tokio book that i adapted.

step 4 — i grep'd the codebase for `tokio::select!` and read each one. there were 4. three were correct (had explicit cancel branches). the fourth — the one in the request handler — did not call `.abort()` on the work handle when the timeout branch fired. that was the bug. once i saw it, i actually said 'ay no manches' out loud at 11pm in the kitchen. nube woke up, looked at me, decided i was fine, went back to sleep.

step 5 — fix was small, took 30 minutes once i found it:

```rust
let work_handle = tokio::spawn(async move {
    optimizer.solve(&stops).await
});

let result = tokio::select! {
    biased;
    res = &mut work_handle => res,
    _ = sleep(timeout) => {
        work_handle.abort();        // <-- this line was missing
        Err(Error::Timeout)
    }
};
```

the `biased;` is also load-bearing — it tells select to evaluate branches in order, so if both fire simultaneously (which can happen on fast machines under burst), we always take the result branch. the `&mut` on `work_handle` matters too: without it, the handle is moved into select on first poll and the abort path can't reach it. small thing, easy to miss, every rust async dev has hit this once.

step 6 — added a unit test that simulates the timeout path explicitly and checks that the spawned task is aborted within 100ms. snapshot-style assertion using a ref-counted sentinel. this is the kind of test that you only write after you've been bitten — i wouldn't have known to write it before. now it's in the suite forever. test code:

```rust
#[tokio::test]
async fn timeout_aborts_sibling_task() {
    let counter = Arc::new(AtomicUsize::new(0));
    let counter_clone = counter.clone();
    let _ = with_timeout(Duration::from_millis(50), async move {
        // task that would run forever
        tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_secs(60)).await;
        counter_clone.fetch_add(1, Ordering::SeqCst);
    }).await;
    tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_millis(200)).await;
    assert_eq!(counter.load(Ordering::SeqCst), 0,
        "spawned task should have been aborted by timeout");
}
```

step 7 — ran the same load test that surfaced the original growth. memory flat for an hour, then flat for two hours, then flat overnight (i let it run to 7am). shipped the fix to the staging branch. wrote a one-paragraph summary in the project channel: 'memory regression resolved. cause: tokio::select timeout branch not aborting sibling task. fix: explicit abort() in timeout branch. tests added.' didn't elaborate. the team will read the diff if they care. roberto will ask me to elaborate in 1:1 next week, i can already feel it.

carla is going to absolutely roast me when she's back from leave because she warned me against the spawn-per-request pattern in june and i did it anyway because it was simpler. she was right. she's always right. i need to write a blog post about this whose only point is 'always abort sibling tasks on timeout' but that's not a blog post, that's a tokio docs entry that already exists and i just didn't read it carefully enough. there is a section in the tokio book called 'graceful shutdown' that covers exactly this pattern. i bookmarked it eight months ago. did not internalize it. classic engineer-failure-mode: bookmarked = false sense of having learned. like saving a recipe to a pinterest board and then ordering takeout.

órale. fixing this also clears the path for the next blocker, which is the thing carla actually warned me about — the runtime sizing under burst load. that one i'll hit next month. i can already see the contour of the problem: even with this leak fixed, the single-threaded current_thread runtime is going to hit limits under sustained burst, and we'll need to bump to multi_thread. but that's a future-me problem. for now: memory is flat, p95 is 38ms, the postgis encoder is in production-shape, the test suite covers the new abort path. that's a good day, even if today was 14 hours long.

random side note: i found this bug at 11pm last night, fixed it by midnight, and slept like a rock for six hours straight. nothing better for insomnia than fixing a real bug. should bottle it. seriously — there's something about the brain finally exhaling after a week of carrying a problem unsolved that resets every other anxiety dial too. i didn't think about la polar, i didn't think about pacheco, i didn't think about roberto, i didn't think about the kid conversation. just slept. mi reino por un bug bien resuelto.

side-side note: i'm going to write up this debugging story for our internal eng wiki, partially because it's good for the team and partially because i want roberto to see it. proof of senior-engineer-shaped work. paper trail in his world too.
